<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911016-0043</DOCNO><DOCID>911016-0043.</DOCID><HL>   Technology Brief -- Automatic Data Processing Inc.:   Profit Rose 10% in Quarter;   Brokerage Margins Improved</HL><DATE>10/16/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   AUD</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>EARNINGS (ERN)SOFTWARE (SOF)</IN><NS>EARNINGS (ERN)</NS><RE>NEW JERSEY (NJ)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Automatic Data Processing Inc. reported record earningsand revenue for the fiscal first quarter ended Sept. 30.   The computing services company said net income rose 10% to$45.8 million, or 33 cents a share, from $41.7 million, or 29cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue climbed 4% to $429million.</LP><TEXT>   In the latest quarter, the Roseland, N.J., companypurchased about 400,000 shares of its common stock.   Josh S. Weston, chairman, cited &quot;significantly improvedmargins&quot; in services to brokerage firms. &quot;Despite therecession,&quot; he added, &quot;our other core businesses maintainedlast year's margins.&quot;   Mr. Weston said the company continues to expectdouble-digit per-share earnings growth for the full fiscalyear with a modest revenue increase, assuming no change inthe national economic environment.   The company said &quot;although the effect of the recession inemployer services is somewhat deeper than originallyexpected, we are quite satisfied that its largest component,the payroll business, grew 10% over last year.&quot; It said it is&quot;aggressively&quot; pruning such non-core businesses as batchaccounting, time-sharing and distribution services.</TEXT></DOC>